---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('gutter-cleaning-ayr-kilmarnock-spring')!;
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Gutter cleaning',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'gutter cleaning kilmarnock', 'gutter vacuum ayrshire', 'spring gutter clean', 'blocked gutters ayr'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [{ '@type': 'Place', name: 'Ayr, Scotland' }, { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Kilmarnock, Scotland' }],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Everybody books their gutter clean in October. They shouldn’t — they should book it now. Here’s why April is the right month across Ayr, Kilmarnock and the rest of East Ayrshire, and what a proper vac-pole clean actually looks like from the ground.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg">
      <p>
        I spend more weeks of the year up gutters than I’d like to admit. After doing this in the rain, the dark and the middle of February, I can tell you one thing straight: the folk who book their
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/gutter-cleaning/`}>gutter clean in April</a> have half the problems of the folk who leave it until the leaves are already down.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the short version of why spring is the right window for Ayr, Kilmarnock and everywhere between — and what actually happens when we turn up on your lawn with a vac pole.
      </p>

      <h2>Why spring beats autumn (every time)</h2>
      <p>
        The instinct is to clean after the trees drop. Makes sense on paper. In practice it’s the wrong call — three reasons.
      </p>

      <h3>1. Winter’s already done its damage</h3>
      <p>
        If your gutters were blocked through Ayrshire’s wet season — roughly November to March — water has been backing up behind a dam of leaves and moss for four months. Soaking into the fascia, dribbling down the wall behind the downpipe, freezing expansion-cracks into every joint. By April you can <em>see</em> that damage. By October it’s hidden behind a fresh summer’s growth.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most fascia rot, hopper cracks and loose downpipe brackets we find are spotted on spring jobs. Fixing them in April costs a fraction of finding them in October when they’ve had another six months to worsen.
      </p>

      <h3>2. The moss is softer and lighter</h3>
      <p>
        Ayrshire roofs grow moss like a permanent feature. Through summer it dries, hardens and welds itself to the tile joints. In spring it’s still damp from winter — it comes out of the gutter with about half the effort. Job’s quicker, you pay less.
      </p>

      <h3>3. You get the summer for the proper fixes</h3>
      <p>
        If a spring clean flags a sagging run, a leaking joint or a broken bracket, there’s a full dry season ahead to
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/guttering/`}>replace or repair</a> properly. Leave it to autumn and you’re chasing a fix in November weather with the next storm a week away.
      </p>

      <h2>What happens on a gutter clean</h2>
      <p>
        No ladders on the lawn, no boot-marks on the roof, no mess on the driveway. We use a gutter-vac pole system — a long carbon-fibre pole with a camera on the end and a high-suction vac at the base. I stand on the ground, run the pole up, look down the gutter on a screen, and hoover every run clear.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Every gutter, hopper and outlet vac-cleared.</li>
        <li>Downpipes flushed with water to confirm flow.</li>
        <li>Photo of each cleaned run, sent by WhatsApp before we leave.</li>
        <li>Moss and debris bagged and taken away — we pay the tip fee.</li>
        <li>Bracket and joint check while the pole is up there.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        That last point matters more than folk realise. Half the time we clear a blocked gutter and <em>then</em> find a joint that’s been leaking quietly for a year. We photograph it, quote a repair, and you decide. No pressure, no tacking extras onto the invoice — we’d rather leave you with information than a surprise.
      </p>

      <h2>Warning signs you shouldn’t leave till June</h2>
      <p>
        Before you book, walk outside and look up. Any of these, ring us this week:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>A gutter that’s sagging visibly</strong> — the bracket’s failing or the fascia behind it is soft.</li>
        <li><strong>Water staining on the wall</strong> under a joint or hopper — that joint has been leaking a while.</li>
        <li><strong>Plants growing out of the gutter</strong> — silt is deep enough to seed. That run is probably 50% full.</li>
        <li><strong>Water overshooting the gutter in heavy rain</strong> — run blocked, or the gutter has dropped out of level.</li>
        <li><strong>Damp in an upstairs corner of the house</strong> — classic sign that a gutter is backing up and soaking the wall-top through the eaves.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Any of those and it’s not just a clean — it’s a clean <em>and</em> a quote for the repair. We’ll do both in one visit if we can.
      </p>

      <h2>Ayr vs. Kilmarnock — any difference?</h2>
      <p>
        Honest answer: a bit.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a> properties — especially the seafront and Esplanade terraces — get salt-laden air all year. Gutter metalwork and paint take a battering, and the runs at the front of the house silt up with fine sand as well as leaves. We often recommend deep-flow PVC gutters on those streets rather than standard half-round — the volume of water coming off a big slate roof overwhelms the shallower profile in a proper downpour.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock’s</a> older tenement stock around the town centre has back-court gutters that nobody looks at for years at a time. Those are our bread-and-butter spring jobs — big cast-iron runs that haven’t been touched since the building was modernised, usually full of sixty years of silt and one ball a child threw up there in 1987.
      </p>

      <h2>What it costs</h2>
      <p>
        A standard gutter clean starts at <strong>£60 for a small terrace</strong> and runs up to around <strong>£120 for a big detached</strong> with a complex run. We quote straight from a photo — WhatsApp the front and back of the house and you’ll have a firm number inside an hour.
      </p>
      <p>
        No call-out fee in <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/troon/`}>Troon</a>, or anywhere on
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>the East Ayrshire patch</a>. We show up, clean, photograph, tidy, then you pay by card or bank transfer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Book now, not in October. Your fascias will thank you.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTABlock
    heading="Ready for a spring gutter clean in Ayr or Kilmarnock?"
    sub="Send a photo of your house to WhatsApp — we'll quote in an hour and book you in this week."
  />
</BaseLayout>
